Anatomy of a boxplot

Basic boxplot

library(ggplot2)
 
# The mtcars dataset is natively available
head(mtcars)
##                    mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Mazda RX4         21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.620 16.46  0  1    4    4
## Mazda RX4 Wag     21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.875 17.02  0  1    4    4
## Datsun 710        22.8   4  108  93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet 4 Drive    21.4   6  258 110 3.08 3.215 19.44  1  0    3    1
## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant           18.1   6  225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=as.factor(cyl), y=mpg)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill="slateblue", alpha=0.2) + 
  xlab("cyl")

Boxplot parameters

library(ggplot2)
 
# The mpg dataset is natively available
head(mpg)
## # A tibble: 6 × 11
##   manufacturer model displ  year   cyl trans      drv     cty   hwy fl    class  
##   <chr>        <chr> <dbl> <int> <int> <chr>      <chr> <int> <int> <chr> <chr>  
## 1 audi         a4      1.8  1999     4 auto(l5)   f        18    29 p     compact
## 2 audi         a4      1.8  1999     4 manual(m5) f        21    29 p     compact
## 3 audi         a4      2    2008     4 manual(m6) f        20    31 p     compact
## 4 audi         a4      2    2008     4 auto(av)   f        21    30 p     compact
## 5 audi         a4      2.8  1999     6 auto(l5)   f        16    26 p     compact
## 6 audi         a4      2.8  1999     6 manual(m5) f        18    26 p     compact

# geom_boxplot proposes several arguments to custom appearance
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=class, y=hwy)) + 
  geom_boxplot(
    color="blue", fill="blue", alpha=0.2,
    notch=TRUE, notchwidth = 0.8,
    outlier.colour="red", outlier.fill="red", outlier.size=3
  )

Reorder a variable

library(forcats)
library(dplyr)

# reorder using median
mpg <- mpg %>% mutate(class = fct_reorder(class, hwy, .fun='median'))
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=class, y=hwy, fill=class)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + theme(legend.position="none")

# reorder using number of observation per group
mpg <- mpg %>% mutate(class = fct_reorder(class, hwy, .fun='length'))
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=class, y=hwy, fill=class)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + theme(legend.position="none")

Color customization

# Set a unique color with fill, colour, and alpha
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=class, y=hwy)) + 
    geom_boxplot(color="red", fill="orange", alpha=0.2)

# Set a different color for each group
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=class, y=hwy, fill=class)) + 
    geom_boxplot() +
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="BuPu")

# Set a different color for each group
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=class, y=hwy, fill=class)) + 
    geom_boxplot() +
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")

Highlighting a group

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(hrbrthemes)

# Add a column called 'type': do we want to highlight the group or not?
mpg <- mpg %>% mutate(type=ifelse(class=="subcompact","Highlighted","Normal"))

head(mpg)
## # A tibble: 6 × 12
##   manufacturer model displ  year   cyl trans      drv     cty   hwy fl    class   type  
##   <chr>        <chr> <dbl> <int> <int> <chr>      <chr> <int> <int> <chr> <fct>   <chr> 
## 1 audi         a4      1.8  1999     4 auto(l5)   f        18    29 p     compact Normal
## 2 audi         a4      1.8  1999     4 manual(m5) f        21    29 p     compact Normal
## 3 audi         a4      2    2008     4 manual(m6) f        20    31 p     compact Normal
## 4 audi         a4      2    2008     4 auto(av)   f        21    30 p     compact Normal
## 5 audi         a4      2.8  1999     6 auto(l5)   f        16    26 p     compact Normal
## 6 audi         a4      2.8  1999     6 manual(m5) f        18    26 p     compact Normal

# Build the boxplot. In the 'fill' argument, give this column
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=class, y=hwy, fill=type, alpha=type)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#69b3a2", "grey")) +
  scale_alpha_manual(values=c(1,0.1)) +
  theme_ipsum() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  xlab("")

Grouped boxplot

library(ggplot2)
 
# create a data frame
data <- data.frame(
  variety = rep(LETTERS[1:7], each=40),
  treatment = rep(c("high","low"), each=20),
  note = seq(1:280) + sample(1:150, 280, replace=T)
)

head(data)
##   variety treatment note
## 1       A      high   22
## 2       A      high   43
## 3       A      high   19
## 4       A      high  108
## 5       A      high  132
## 6       A      high  151

# the group must be called in the X argument. 
# the subgroup is called in the fill argument. 
ggplot(data, aes(x=variety, y=note, fill=treatment)) + 
    geom_boxplot()

Using small multiple

# One box per treatment
ggplot(data, aes(x=variety, y=note, fill=treatment)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~treatment)

# one box per variety
ggplot(data, aes(x=variety, y=note, fill=treatment)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~variety, scale="free")

Boxplot with width proportionnal to sample size

library(ggplot2)
 
# create data
names <- c(rep("A", 20), rep("B", 5), rep("C", 30), rep("D", 100))
value <- c(sample(2:5, 20, replace=T), 
           sample(4:10, 5, replace=T), 
           sample(1:7, 30, replace=T), 
           sample(3:8, 100, replace=T)
          )
data <- data.frame(names, value)
head(data)
##   names value
## 1     A     5
## 2     A     2
## 3     A     3
## 4     A     3
## 5     A     2
## 6     A     2

# prepare a special xlab with the number of obs for each group
my_xlab <- paste(levels(data$names),"\n(N=",table(data$names),")",sep="")
 
ggplot(data, aes(x=names, y=value, fill=names)) +
  geom_boxplot(varwidth = TRUE, alpha=0.2) +
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels=my_xlab)

Boxplot from continuous variable

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(hrbrthemes)


# Start with the diamonds dataset, natively available in R:
diamonds <- diamonds %>%
  # Add a new column called 'bin': cut the initial 'carat' in bins
  mutate(bin=cut_width(carat, width=0.5, boundary=0))

head(diamonds)
## # A tibble: 6 × 11
##   carat cut       color clarity depth table price     x     y     z bin    
##   <dbl> <ord>     <ord> <ord>   <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <fct>  
## 1  0.23 Ideal     E     SI2      61.5    55   326  3.95  3.98  2.43 [0,0.5]
## 2  0.21 Premium   E     SI1      59.8    61   326  3.89  3.84  2.31 [0,0.5]
## 3  0.23 Good      E     VS1      56.9    65   327  4.05  4.07  2.31 [0,0.5]
## 4  0.29 Premium   I     VS2      62.4    58   334  4.2   4.23  2.63 [0,0.5]
## 5  0.31 Good      J     SI2      63.3    58   335  4.34  4.35  2.75 [0,0.5]
## 6  0.24 Very Good J     VVS2     62.8    57   336  3.94  3.96  2.48 [0,0.5]

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=bin, y=price)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill="#69b3a2") +
  theme_ipsum() +
  xlab("Carat")

Boxplot with mean value

library(ggplot2)
 
# create data
names <- c(rep("A", 20), rep("B", 8), rep("C", 30), rep("D", 80))
value <- c(sample(2:5, 20, replace=T), 
           sample(4:10, 8, replace=T), 
           sample(1:7, 30, replace=T), 
           sample(3:8, 80, replace=T)
          )
data <- data.frame(names, value)
head(data)
##   names value
## 1     A     4
## 2     A     5
## 3     A     5
## 4     A     5
## 5     A     4
## 6     A     2

ggplot(data, aes(x=names, y=value, fill=names)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha=0.7) +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, geom="point", shape=20, size=14, color="red", fill="red") +
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set1")

Boxplot with individual data points

library(tidyverse)
library(hrbrthemes)
library(viridis)

# create a dataset
data <- data.frame(
  name=c(rep("A",500), rep("B",500), rep("B",500), rep("C",20), rep('D', 100)),
  value=c(rnorm(500, 10, 5), rnorm(500, 13, 1), rnorm(500, 18, 1), rnorm(20, 25, 4), rnorm(100, 12, 1))
)

head(data)
##   name     value
## 1    A  8.613457
## 2    A  2.729143
## 3    A  8.297990
## 4    A  5.141680
## 5    A 12.322382
## 6    A  3.566034

ggplot(data, aes(x=name, y=value, fill=name)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, alpha=0.6) +
  geom_jitter(color="black", size=0.4, alpha=0.9) +
  theme_ipsum() +
  theme(legend.position="none", plot.title = element_text(size=11)) +
  ggtitle("A boxplot with jitter") + xlab("")

Marginal distribution

library(ggplot2)
library(ggExtra)
 
# The mtcars dataset is proposed in R
head(mtcars)
##                    mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Mazda RX4         21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.620 16.46  0  1    4    4
## Mazda RX4 Wag     21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.875 17.02  0  1    4    4
## Datsun 710        22.8   4  108  93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet 4 Drive    21.4   6  258 110 3.08 3.215 19.44  1  0    3    1
## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant           18.1   6  225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1

p <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=wt, y=mpg, color=cyl, size=cyl)) +
      geom_point() +
      theme(legend.position="none")

# marginal boxplot
ggMarginal(p, type="boxplot")
